---
import ArticleLayout from '../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
import Reassurance from '../components/Reassurance.astro';
import MidCta from '../components/MidCta.astro';
import PullQuote from '../components/PullQuote.astro';
import FaqSection from '../components/FaqSection.astro';
import CtaBlock from '../components/CtaBlock.astro';
import EnquiryForm from '../components/locked/EnquiryForm.astro';
import RelatedPanel from '../components/RelatedPanel.astro';

const slug = '/can-a-seafarer-get-a-mortgage';

const reassuranceLines = [
  'Steady contracted income, paid on rotation.',
  'Pay arriving in US dollars or euros.',
  'A low tax bill from the Seafarers Earnings Deduction.',
  'Long, regular spells working away at sea.',
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Can a seafarer get a mortgage in the UK?',
    a: 'Yes. A seafarer with a steady contract and a reasonable deposit can get a UK mortgage. Seafarers are strong borrowers, so eligibility is rarely the problem. The real task is choosing a lender whose assessment reads your income, residency and time at sea correctly rather than penalising them.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Why do some lenders turn a seafarer down?',
    a: 'Usually because an automated check has misread the case rather than because the borrower fails the rules. Foreign currency pay, a low tax figure from the Seafarers Earnings Deduction, or gaps that look like time out of work can all trip a system that was not built for seafarers. A lender that understands the role assesses the same facts and reaches a different answer.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does living abroad stop a seafarer getting a mortgage?',
    a: 'Not on its own, but it narrows the list. UK-resident seafarers usually have the widest choice and standard deposit levels, subject to criteria. Non-resident cases tend to need a larger deposit and a shorter list of lenders will consider them. Your residency and UK ties shape which lenders help, not whether help exists.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I start?',
    a: 'Use the 60-second check and a Mortgage One adviser will review your answers and tell you where you stand. You can also call us on 01202 155992. You must be on UK soil to receive advice.',
  },
];

const relatedCards = [
  { title: 'Mortgages for seafarers', href: '/mortgage-as-a-seafarer', line: 'The full picture for seafarer mortgages.' },
  { title: 'Foreign currency income', href: '/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income', line: 'How lenders convert and discount non-sterling pay.' },
  { title: 'Seafarers Earnings Deduction mortgages', href: '/seafarers-earnings-deduction-mortgage', line: 'Getting a mortgage while you claim the Seafarers Earnings Deduction.' },
  { title: 'Check your eligibility', href: '/check', line: 'Five quick questions, about 60 seconds.' },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="Can a Seafarer Get a Mortgage? | Mortgage One"
  description="Yes, seafarers can get a UK mortgage. What a lender actually checks on income, residency and deposit, and why a specialist beats an automated decision."
  eyebrow="Seafarer mortgage questions"
  heading="Can a seafarer get a mortgage?"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { name: 'Can a seafarer get a mortgage?', href: slug },
  ]}
  scenario="seafarer"
>
  <p>
    Yes. Seafarers get UK mortgages across multiple lenders in the market. A steady contract and a reasonable deposit
    make a seafarer a strong borrower, so eligibility is rarely the obstacle. The obstacle, when there is one, is lender
    choice: pick a lender whose assessment reads seafarer income properly and a yes is well within reach.
  </p>

  <Reassurance title="Situations we see regularly" lines={reassuranceLines} />

  <h2>What does a lender actually assess?</h2>
  <p>
    A lender looks at three things in particular: your income and the evidence behind it, your residency and UK ties, and
    your deposit. On income, it wants to see pay that is real, regular and likely to continue, backed by your contract,
    payslips and bank statements. On residency, it weighs where you are tax resident and how much recent UK address
    history you have. On deposit, the size of it sets your loan to value and the rates you can reach. None of these
    counts against a seafarer by default. They are simply the facts a lender measures, and a seafarer usually measures
    up well.
  </p>

  <h2>Why does an automated check say no when a specialist says yes?</h2>
  <p>
    Because a high-street system is built around a UK-based, sterling-paid, nine-to-five borrower, and a seafarer does
    not fit that template at a glance. Three features trip the machine without troubling a specialist underwriter. Pay in
    a foreign currency can look like instability rather than a normal contract. A low tax bill from the Seafarers
    Earnings Deduction (SED) can read as a low income when your gross pay is healthy. Long spells at sea can look like
    gaps in employment rather than the rotation they are. A lender that understands seafarers sees the same facts and
    reads them correctly.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Had a no that did not add up? Tell us how you are paid and we will tell you where you stand."
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <h2>How do foreign currency pay and the SED change the decision?</h2>
  <p>
    They change which lender suits you, not whether you qualify. With foreign currency pay, a lender converts your income
    to sterling and applies a reduction to allow for the rate moving, then lends on that figure. The size of the
    reduction varies between lenders, which is why the lender matters more than the rate. We cover this on our
    <a href="/seafarer-mortgage-foreign-currency-income">foreign currency income</a> page. With the SED, the deduction
    lowers your tax, not your earnings, and the right lender works from your gross contractual pay rather than the low tax
    figure on your return. Our <a href="/seafarers-earnings-deduction-mortgage">Seafarers Earnings Deduction</a> page
    sets out the evidence a lender will want.
  </p>

  <PullQuote quote="For a seafarer, the question is rarely whether a mortgage is possible. It is which lender reads your income the way it really works." />

  <h2>Does residency and UK ties affect eligibility?</h2>
  <p>
    They shape the list of lenders and the deposit, rather than closing the door. A UK-resident seafarer with a recent
    address history usually has the widest choice and can often reach standard deposit levels, subject to criteria. A
    non-resident seafarer tends to need a larger deposit, and a shorter list of lenders will consider the case. Either
    way there is a route. You must be on UK soil to receive advice, so we confirm your circumstances properly before
    pointing you anywhere.
  </p>

  <h2>What makes a seafarer easy to say yes to?</h2>
  <p>
    A clear contract that states your role, rate and rotation. Payslips and bank statements that show the pay arriving
    and, where relevant, converting to sterling. A short written note where your income has moved between currencies or
    employers, so an underwriter sees the pattern rather than guesses at it. Put the right paperwork in front of the
    right lender and a seafarer case becomes a straightforward one. Mortgage One has access to plans from the whole of
    market and gives professional advice on where your case fits.
  </p>

  <MidCta
    text="Find out where you stand before you apply, not after a needless decline."
    label="Check Your Options"
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <FaqSection items={faqs} />

  <CtaBlock
    heading="See whether you qualify"
    line="Tell us how you are paid and a Mortgage One adviser will review your answers."
    scenario="seafarer"
    src={slug}
  />

  <h2>Send us an enquiry</h2>
  <EnquiryForm scenario="seafarer" />

  <RelatedPanel cards={relatedCards} />

  <p class="risk-warning">
    Think carefully before securing your debts against your home. Your home may be repossessed if you do not keep up
    repayments on your mortgage.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>

<style>
  .risk-warning {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
  }
</style>
